Partial Least Squares (PLS) regression

for regression and classification

Payam Emami

Agenda

  • Motivation: Why we need supervised dimensionality reduction
  • PCA: Find directions of variance in X
  • CCA: Maximize correlation between X and Y
  • PLS: Maximize covariance between X and Y
  • PLS-DA: Use PLS for classification tasks
  • Validation: R², Q², cross-validation
  • Interpretation: Loadings, scores, VIP scores
  • Data Integration: Multi-omics with block-wise PLS

Why Learn PLS?

  • High-dimensional data: \(p \gg n\)

  • Strong correlations among features

  • Need interpretable predictive components

  • Want to relate X (predictors) to Y (response) where both can be matrices

  • Omics data (genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics)

  • Chemometrics and quality control

  • Data integration across multiple blocks (multi-omics, multi-view)

Let’s see how PCA works under the hood

  • PCA rotates the data so that the new axes align with the directions of maximum variance.
    • This is done using covariance matrix (ellipsoid)
  • Calculate the major axis of the ellipsoid: compute the first eigenvector of the covariance matrix, it gives the direction of maximum variance.
  • Reconstruct and deflate the data: project the data onto the first principal axis, then subtract this projection to remove the explained variance and reveal the remaining structure.

Let’s see how PCA works under the hood

  • PCA rotates the data so that the new axes align with the directions of maximum variance.
    • This is done using covariance matrix (ellipsoid)
  • Calculate the major axis of the ellipsoid: compute the first eigenvector of the covariance matrix, it gives the direction of maximum variance.
  • Reconstruct and deflate the data: project the data onto the first principal axis, then subtract this projection to remove the explained variance and reveal the remaining structure.
  • Repeat

More technically

Let \(X \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p}\) be mean-centered data.

  1. Compute covariance matrix
    \[ S = \frac{1}{n} X^{\mathsf T} X \]

  2. Eigen decomposition: \(S = V \Lambda V^{\mathsf T}\)

    • Columns of \(V\): principal directions (eigenvectors)
    • Diagonal of \(\Lambda\): variances (eigenvalues)

  3. Extract first component: \(w_1 = \text{first eigenvector}, \quad t_1 = X w_1\)

    • \(t_1\) are the PC1 scores (projection)

  4. Deflate the data
    \[ X^{(1)} = X - t_1 w_1^{\mathsf T} \]

  5. Repeat on residuals

    • Perform PCA again on \(X^{(1)}\)
    • Get \(w_2, t_2\), deflate again
    • Continue until desired number of components extracted

Alternative: via Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)

SVD of \(X\):

\[ X = U D V^{\mathsf T} \]

  • Columns of \(V\): loadings (same as eigenvectors of \(S\))
  • Columns of \(U D\): scores (principal components)

This is equivalent and numerically more stable in high dimensions.

Variance Lives on the Diagonal

This is what PCA is really about it’s all sitting on the diagonal!

\[ S = \begin{bmatrix} \color{red}{2.5} & 1.2 & 0.5 & 1.0 & 0.8 \\ 1.2 & \color{red}{3.1} & 0.9 & 1.5 & 1.1 \\ 0.5 & 0.9 & \color{red}{2.8} & 0.7 & 0.4 \\ 1.0 & 1.5 & 0.7 & \color{red}{3.3} & 1.2 \\ 0.8 & 1.1 & 0.4 & 1.2 & \color{red}{2.9} \end{bmatrix} \]

  • Diagonal elements (in red):
    \(\text{Var}(X_1), \text{Var}(X_2), \dots, \text{Var}(X_5)\)

  • Off-diagonal:
    How features co-vary e.g., \(\text{Cov}(X_2, X_4) = 1.5\)

  • PCA finds a rotation of the axes such that:

    • The new covariance matrix is diagonal
    • The diagonal entries now represent the variance along the new axes

  • PCA maximizes one diagonal value at a time
    \[ \max_{w} \quad w^{\mathsf T} S w \quad \text{subject to } \|w\| = 1 \]

What if we want to make PCA supervised?

Let’s say I have another dataset \(Y\), and I want PCA not just to show me the directions of highest variance in \(X\), but rather the directions in \(X\) that are most useful for explaining or predicting \(Y\).

If we want to guide the eigen decomposition algorithm using \(Y\), we need to incorporate information about \(Y\) into the square matrix (which we previously called the covariance matrix) that drives the decomposition.

In PCA, this matrix is \(X^\top X\), which only contains information about variance within \(X\). To bring \(Y\) into the picture, we need a new matrix that reflects how \(X\) and \(Y\) interact. One natural choice is the cross-covariance matrix \(X^\top Y\), which tells us how each variable in \(X\) co-varies with each variable in \(Y\).

The Cross-Covariance Matrix

Suppose we have two centered datasets:

  • \(X \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p}\): predictors
  • \(Y \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times q}\): responses

We define the cross-covariance matrix between \(X\) and \(Y\) as:

\[ C_{XY} = \frac{1}{n} X^\top Y \]

This matrix has shape \(p \times q\), and each entry\((i, j)\) shows how much feature \(X_i\) co-varies with feature \(Y_j\) across the samples.

         [,1]        [,2]
[1,] 3.150913 -1.06559666
[2,] 2.199966 -0.07108427
[3,] 1.145256 -0.39498518
  • The cross-covariance matrix captures the linear relationships between variables in \(X\) and variables in \(Y\)
  • It contains exactly the information we want when we’re trying to find directions in \(X\) that are most predictive of \(Y\)

Fixing the Square Matrix

The cross-covariance matrix \(X^\top Y\) has shape \(p \times q\), so we can’t diagonalize it directly. But we can build a square matrix from it that still captures the relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\).

Let’s define:

\[ M = X^\top Y Y^\top X \]

  • This matrix has shape \(p \times p\), just like the covariance matrix \(X^\top X\) in PCA.
  • It is symmetric and positive semi-definite, so we can perform eigen decomposition.

Think of this matrix as measuring: “How strongly does each direction in \(X\) contribute to predicting \(Y\), and how redundant are those directions with each other?”

What’s on the Diagonal and Off-Diagonal in \(M\)

Let’s interpret the entries of \(M = X^\top Y Y^\top X\):

  • Diagonal entries \(M_{ii}\) measure how strongly feature \(X_i\) is associated with all of Y, aggregated across all response variables and samples.

    • If \(M_{11}\) is large, it means \(X_1\) is very useful in predicting \(Y\).
    • These are signal strengths for individual features in \(X\).

  • Off-diagonal entries \(M_{ij}\) measure shared predictive power between \(X_i\) and \(X_j\).

    • If \(M_{12}\) is large, it means \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) are both predictive of similar aspects of \(Y\).
    • These reflect redundancy or correlation in how features contribute to predicting \(Y\).

So in a sense:

  • Diagonal = importance of each feature for predicting \(Y\)
  • Off-diagonal = overlap in what features predict about \(Y\)

Example

Example (cross covariance)

Now we calculate the cross covariance and plot it:

Example (eigenvectors)

  • \(X^\top Y Y^\top X\) gives components in the X-space.
  • To get components in the Y-space, use \(Y^\top X X^\top Y\).
  • Both capture the same cross-covariance but in their own coordinate systems.
  • Rotate both \(X\) and \(Y\) to find aligned directions in each space.

Final deflation

\[ X_{\text{new}} = X - \mathbf{t} \mathbf{p}^\top, \quad \text{where } \mathbf{p} = \frac{X^\top \mathbf{t}}{\mathbf{t}^\top \mathbf{t}} \]

\[ Y_{\text{new}} = Y - \mathbf{t} \mathbf{q}^\top, \quad \text{where } \mathbf{q} = \frac{Y^\top \mathbf{t}}{\mathbf{t}^\top \mathbf{t}} \]

  • X is deflated using its own projection \(\mathbf{t}\) → removes variation already captured (as in PCA).
  • Y is deflated using the same \(\mathbf{t}\) from X → ensures we only keep what is not yet explained by X.

After we do the deflation we redo the covariance calculation and start from the beginning.

Final deflation

  • \(X^\top Y Y^\top X\) gives components in the X-space.
  • To get components in the Y-space, use \(Y^\top X X^\top Y\).
  • Both capture the same cross-covariance but in their own coordinate systems.
  • Rotate both \(X\) and \(Y\) to find aligned directions in each space.

Projecting X and Y into Latent Space (PLS)

Get the weights

  • X weight (from eigen decomposition):

    \[ \mathbf{w} = \text{first eigenvector of } X^\top Y Y^\top X \]

  • Y weight (aligned with \(\mathbf{t}\)):

    \[ \mathbf{q} = \frac{Y^\top \mathbf{t}}{\mathbf{t}^\top \mathbf{t}}, \quad \text{where } \mathbf{t} = X \mathbf{w} \]

Project X and Y

  • Latent score from X:

    \[ \mathbf{t} = X \mathbf{w} \]

  • Latent score from Y:

    \[ \mathbf{u} = Y \mathbf{q} \] \(\mathbf{t}\) captures direction in \(X\) most predictive of \(Y\). \(\mathbf{u}\) is the matching direction in \(Y\), maximally aligned with \(\mathbf{t}\).

Projection

In R we can use mixOmics package to sort out everything for us

library(mixOmics)
pls_model<-pls(X = X,Y = Y,ncomp = 2)
plotIndiv(pls_model)

Partial Least Squares (PLS)

  • Maximize the covariance between \(X\mathbf{w}\) and \(Y\mathbf{q}\)
  • Learn latent components that are predictive and low-dimensional

Let:

  • \(\mathbf{w}\): weight vector in \(X\)-space
  • \(\mathbf{q}\): weight vector in \(Y\)-space
  • \(\mathbf{t} = X \mathbf{w}\): latent score from \(X\)
  • \(\mathbf{u} = Y \mathbf{q}\): latent score from \(Y\)

\[ \max_{\|\mathbf{w}\| = 1, \|\mathbf{q}\| = 1} \; \text{Cov}(X \mathbf{w}, Y \mathbf{q}) = \mathbf{w}^\top X^\top Y \mathbf{q} \]

Latent components:

\[ \mathbf{T} = X \mathbf{W}, \quad \mathbf{U} = Y \mathbf{Q} \] * Can be used for regression:

\[ Y \approx \mathbf{T} \mathbf{B}, \quad \text{where } \mathbf{B} = (\mathbf{T}^\top \mathbf{T})^{-1} \mathbf{T}^\top Y \]

Validation of PLS

Like any other supervised method, we must validate PLS before interpreting or using it for prediction.

We typically assess:

R²X — Explained Variance in X

\[ R^2_X = \frac{\text{Variance explained by the components in } X}{\text{Total variance in } X} \]

  • Shows how well the model summarizes the predictors.

R²Y:Explained Variance in Y

\[ R^2_Y = \frac{\text{Variance explained by the components in } Y}{\text{Total variance in } Y} \]

  • Reflects how well \(Y\) is fitted by the model.
  • Higher \(R^2_Y\) means better in-sample fit.

Q²: Predictive Ability (Cross-Validated \(R^2_Y\))

\[ Q^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum_{k=1}^{Q} \text{PRESS}^h_k}{\sum_{k=1}^{Q} \text{RSS}^0_k} \]

Where:

  • \(\text{PRESS}^h_k = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i^{(h)} - \hat{y}_i^{(h)(-i)})^2\): Prediction error for each Y-variable \(k\) using leave-one-out or K-fold CV.
  • \(\text{RSS}^0_k = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i^{(h)} - \bar{y}_k)^2\): Residual sum of squares using the mean of Y as predictor (null model).

This \(Q^2\) assesses the marginal contribution of component \(h\) to the model’s predictive power, as defined by Tenenhaus (1998) and implemented by Chavent & Patouille (2003).

A rule of thumb:

\[ Q^2 \geq 1 - 0.95^2 = 0.0975 \]

means the component contributes meaningfully to prediction.

Validation of PLS

pls_model<-pls(X = X,Y = Y,ncomp =3,mode = "regression",scale = FALSE)
perf_pls<-perf(pls_model,validation = "loo")
print(1-cumprod(1-perf_pls$measures$Q2.total$values$value))
[1] 0.4237092 0.7695074 0.7875983
plot(perf_pls,"Q2.total")

Variable importance (VIP)

  • VIP scores tell us how important each predictor (X-variable) is in explaining or predicting the outcome Y.

  • It combines:

    • How much each component explains Y (via \(R^2_Y\))
    • How strongly each variable contributes to the components (via squared loadings \(w_{jh}^2\))

\[ \text{VIP}_j = \sqrt{p \cdot \sum_{h=1}^{H} \left( \frac{R^2_{Y,h}}{\sum_{h=1}^{H} R^2_{Y,h}} \cdot w_{jh}^2 \right)} \]

Where:

  • \(p\): number of variables in X
  • \(H\): number of components
  • \(R^2_{Y,h}\): how well component \(h\) explains Y
  • \(w_{jh}\): loading (weight) of variable \(j\) in component \(h\)

✔ VIP > 1 → variable is important ✘ VIP < 1 → less contribution to prediction

Example in R

vip_pls_model<-vip(pls_model)
print(vip_pls_model)
       comp1     comp2     comp3
X1 1.1670428 1.2144690 1.1956095
X2 0.8706446 0.9035354 0.9128069
X3 0.9380773 0.8418366 0.8586626

PLS

  • PLS is a supervised projection method: Finds directions in \(X\) that best predict \(Y\).

  • It handles:

    • Collinearity in predictors
    • Multivariate responses
    • High-dimensional data (\(p \gg n\))

  • Outputs:

    • Latent components \(\mathbf{T} = XW\)
    • Regression model \(Y \approx \mathbf{T}B\)

  • Can be validated using: \(R^2_X\), \(R^2_Y\), and \(Q^2\)

Partial Least Squares Discriminant Analysis (PLS-DA)

  • PLS-DA is just PLS applied to a categorical Y

    • We encode class labels as dummy variables (e.g., one-hot)

  • The rest is the same:

    • Use PLS to find components that best separate classes
    • Projection is guided by supervised information

  • Instead of \(R^2_Y\), we evaluate using:

    • Accuracy, AUC, confusion matrix, cross-validation error
Sample Class Label One-Hot Encoded \(Y\)
1 A (1, 0, 0)
2 B (0, 1, 0)
3 C (0, 0, 1)
4 A (1, 0, 0)

Example in R

I have simulated some data based on 3 classes and the idea is to see if we can “separate” the classes using PLSDA

plsda_model<-plsda(X,class_labels)
plotIndiv(plsda_model)

Model validation

Do NOT trust PLSDA scores. Always validate your model using cross validation

plsda_model_perf<-perf(plsda_model)
plot(plsda_model_perf)

X, Y space and prediction

We use a distance matrix in \(Y\) to do classification! When a new sample comes. we first project to \(X\) then from \(X\)-space to \(Y\) using regression (PLS) and measure the distances to the center of the classes. The closest one will be the predicted classes.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(plsda_model$variates$X,col=as.factor(class_labels),main="X")
plot(plsda_model$variates$Y,col=as.factor(class_labels),main="Y")

Variable selection

  • In mixOmics, the correlation plot shows how strongly each variable in \(X\) is correlated with the PLS-DA components.
  • Variables with high absolute correlation are likely important for discriminating between classes.
  • You can use this to visually select variables that contribute most to class separation.
  • Works well with sparse PLS-DA (splsda) to highlight variables with strongest group-specific signals.
plotVar(plsda_model)

Multiomics data (DIABLO)

  • A multiblock extension of PLS for integrating multiple datasets (e.g., transcriptomics, proteomics, metabolomics).
  • Learns components for each dataset that:
    • Predict the outcome (Y), and
    • Are maximally correlated across datasets, based on prior expectations.

PLS for multiomics data

Let’s say we have 3 datasets \(A\), \(B\) and \(C\). and we have \(Y\) (our outcome) We do PLS on each dataset separate and extract only the first components for each dataset:

\[ t_A^{(1)},\ t_B^{(1)},\ t_C^{(1)}\ \text{(from PLS)} \]

Let’s say we want to guide each dataset’s component using how much we expect it to co-vary with the others.
This is called in the design matrix \(C\):

\[ C = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0.5 \\ 1 & 0 & 0.2 \\ 0.5 & 0.2 & 0 \end{bmatrix} \]

Weighted combination (for sample \(i\)) give us an average score:

\[ z_i^{(q)} = \sum_{k \neq q} C_{qk} \cdot t_i^{(k)} \]

PLS for multiomics data

To update loadings for dataset \(q\), we compute:

\[ w_q^{\text{new}} = \frac{X_q^\top z^{(q)}}{\| X_q^\top z^{(q)} \|} \]

We compute the new latent component:

\[ t_q^{\text{new}} = X_q w_q^{\text{new}} \]

This is the projected value of each sample in dataset \(q\) along the new direction. We use these set of scores and weights for deflating the original datasets. The idea is that we want to explain variance in \(Y\) using the shared information across the datasets!

DIABLO in R

I have simulate two more datasets now we have \(X\), \(X2\) and \(X3\):

# Create named list for DIABLO
data_list <- list(X1 = X, X2 = X2, X3 = X3)

# create design matrix:

design <- matrix(c(0, 0.8, 0.5,
                   0.8, 0, 0.3,
                   0.5, 0.3, 0), nrow = 3)

print(design)
     [,1] [,2] [,3]
[1,]  0.0  0.8  0.5
[2,]  0.8  0.0  0.3
[3,]  0.5  0.3  0.0

DIABLO in R

We can check whether the correlation between components from each data set has been maximised as specified in the design matrix.

diablo_model <- block.plsda(X = data_list, Y = class_labels, design = design, ncomp = 2)
plotDiablo(diablo_model, ncomp = 1)

DIABLO in R

We can project each sample into the space spanned by the components of each block. Clustering of the samples can be better assessed with this plot.

diablo_model <- block.plsda(X = data_list, Y = class_labels, design = design, ncomp = 2)
plotIndiv(diablo_model)

Validation

Similar to PLS-DA, DIABLO model must be validated. The predictions however are now average prediction or majority of votes between different datasets.

diablo_model_perf <- perf(diablo_model)

plot(diablo_model_perf)

Similarities across modalities

The best starting point to evaluate the correlation structure between variables is with the correlation circle plot.

plotVar(diablo_model, var.names = FALSE, 
        style = 'graphics', legend = TRUE,
        pch = c(16, 17, 15), cex = c(2,2,2), 
        col = c('darkorchid', 'brown1', 'lightgreen'))

DIABLO

  • DIABLO is a supervised multiblock method that:

    • Learns components per dataset
    • Aligns them using a design matrix
    • Optimizes both prediction and cross-dataset agreement

  • The design matrix is the core controller:

    • High values = enforce agreement between datasets
    • Zero = no alignment required

  • Validation = like PLS-DA, but across all blocks

  • Variable plots (e.g., plotVar, network) help interpret shared vs unique signals

Final Thoughts & Practical Tips

  • Always center and scale your data
  • Choose number of components via cross-validation or use mixOmics tuning function
  • In DIABLO, define a meaningful design matrix
  • Validate using perf(), check stability and predictive performance
  • Be cautious of overfitting, especially with small sample sizes
set.seed(123)
n_samples <- 1000
n_vars <- 2000

X_random <- matrix(rnorm(n_samples * n_vars), nrow = n_samples, ncol = n_vars)

# Assign random class labels (3 classes)
Y_random <- factor(sample(c("A", "B", "C"), size = n_samples, replace = TRUE))

# Fit PLS-DA model
plsda_random <- plsda(X_random, Y_random, ncomp = 2)

# Plot the sample projection
plotIndiv(plsda_random, comp = 1:2, 
          group = Y_random, 
          legend = TRUE, 
          title = "PLS-DA on Random Data")
